1. Enable Git in PyCharm
Go to File > Settings > Version Control > Git.

Make sure the Path to Git executable is correctly set.

On Windows: usually C:\Program Files\Git\bin\git.exe

On macOS/Linux: usually /usr/bin/git

Click Test to confirm it works.

2. Initialize Git in Your Project
If Git is not already initialized:

Go to VCS > Enable Version Control Integration.

Choose Git from the dropdown.

PyCharm will initialize a Git repository in your project folder.

ðŸš€ Steps to Push Code
1. Add Files to Git
Go to the Git tab (usually bottom-right) or right-click on files > Git > Add.

Or press Ctrl+Alt+A (Windows/Linux) or Cmd+Alt+A (Mac).

2. Commit Changes
Go to VCS > Commit or press Ctrl+K / Cmd+K.

Write a commit message and select the files to commit.

Click Commit or Commit and Push.

3. Set Remote Repository (if not yet set)
Go to Git > Manage Remotes.

Click + and paste your remote repository URL (e.g., from GitHub).

4. Push to Remote
Go to VCS > Git > Push, or press Ctrl+Shift+K / Cmd+Shift+K.

Select the branch and click Push.

ðŸ’¡ Optional: First-Time GitHub Push (New Repo)
If this is your first push to a new GitHub repo:

Create a new repo on GitHub (without README if you already have one locally).

Copy the URL.

In terminal (or PyCharm terminal), add the remote manually:

bash
Copy
Edit
git remote add origin https://github.com/yourusername/yourrepo.git
git push -u origin master  # or main, depending on your branch